<p>Tennessee receives excellent solar irradiance throughout the year, with annual averages ranging from 4.2 to 5.0 peak sun hours depending on location. The western and central regions of the state, including Memphis and Nashville areas, typically see higher solar production potential compared to the mountainous eastern regions. Peak production months occur from April through September, when systems can generate 15-20% above annual averages. Even during winter months, Tennessee's solar resources remain productive, with December and January still providing 60-70% of peak summer production levels.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Tennessee, sized at 6-8kW, can be expected to generate between 7,200-9,600 kWh annually. This production level can offset 70-90% of average household electricity consumption, depending on home size and energy usage patterns. The state's relatively low frequency of severe weather events and minimal shading from atmospheric particles contribute to consistent year-round solar performance. Additionally, Tennessee's moderate temperatures during peak sun hours help maintain panel efficiency, as solar panels perform better in cooler conditions despite needing strong sunlight.</p>

