<h2>Tennessee Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Tennessee offers several valuable incentives that make solar and HVAC investments particularly attractive. The most significant benefit is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the total cost of solar panel installation from their federal taxes. This credit applies to all system components, including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this credit provides \$6,000 in tax savings, and any unused credit can be carried forward to future tax years.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The 30% federal tax credit remains available through 2032, then decreases to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit has no cap and applies to both residential and commercial installations. Homeowners must have sufficient tax liability to claim the full credit, but unused portions can be carried forward for up to five years.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Tennessee offers a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning the added value from solar panels won't increase your property tax assessment. This exemption applies to both the equipment and installation costs, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime.</li>
<li><strong>TVA Energy Right Programs:</strong> The Tennessee Valley Authority offers various rebates for energy-efficient HVAC systems, including up to \$500 for qualifying heat pumps and air conditioning systems. TVA also provides rebates for smart thermostats, ductwork improvements, and other efficiency upgrades that can complement solar installations.</li>
<li><strong>Net Metering Policies:</strong> Most Tennessee utilities offer net metering programs that allow solar system owners to receive credit for excess electricity generated. While policies vary by utility, most provide retail rate credits for surplus generation, effectively using the grid as a battery for solar energy storage.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Many local utilities throughout Tennessee offer additional rebates for HVAC upgrades and energy efficiency improvements. Memphis Light, Gas & Water, Nashville Electric Service, and Chattanooga Electric Power Company all provide various incentive programs that can be combined with federal tax credits.</li>
</ul>

